text: This and the new Ghostbusters reboot will bomb.  The CGI looks absolutely atrocious. Tarzan is not set in a fantasy realm or space, it's set in the jungle. It doesn't need all these effects, They should have used real stunts (i.e Indiana Jones, Mad Max, etc.) This trailer itself probably has more special effects than the original Star Wars trilogy.  They spent 180 million dollars on this movie, not including promotion. Ridiculous for a movie set in the jungle. The two leads are not huge stars. Margot Robbie is a fantastic actress but she is not a huge star like Jennifer Lawrence, Scarlett Johansson, Angelina Jolie, etc. Alexander Skarsgard was part of an ensemble cast on True Blood after leaving the shoe he's been in tons of indie films which have all bombed at the box office. What was Warner Bros. thinking.

text: I avoid commenting on YouTube or starting internet arguments as rule- however, being, a fan of Edgar Rice Burroughs, I have to say something here. Basing your notions of fictional characters and fiction storylines off of movies, rumors and pop culture is a bad idea. I know- I thought John Carter and Tarzan were lame from what I saw in movies, but then I read the books. Books bring so much more depth to stories and characters than a movie is capable of. Tarzan and John Carter are very strong and admirable, and not just physically either. They are also very human characters that bear their own unique imperfections and challenges. Their respective books, while they are "just" fantasy, are engrossing and sensual, even thought provoking at times - all without being obscene or incredibly violent. Are there some words and ideas in Tarzan that are not politically correct to the modern reader? Sure, the books are 100 years old. Is Tarzan about white dominance and racism? Not by my reading. Tarzan is simply a feral man, of English parentage, raised by Apes on the west coast of Africa who discovers his humanity and has to justify his learned feral nature with his newly discovered manhood- a struggle that lasts a lifetime. The apes are Tarzan's people, even though many do not accept the 'hairless white ape'. Animals and apes are his family, friends and teachers for his formative years- not inferiors to be subjugated. I would say Tarzan is racial at times but not racist or supremacist. In fact, Lord Greystoke has more problems and dislikes for what was considered civilised society at that time than he does with the Apes or Natives of Africa.Violence and dominance in Tarzan's world, by and large, has a purpose and is necessary for order and survival. The same in man's world usually has no purpose or need- we practice violence and deceit and cruelty for their own sakes. I encourage some reading to form an educated opinion- not just on this, but on any subject. Go to the source and form your own opinion. Reading some of these uneducated comments about Tarzan... geez I'm at a loss...really, I knew reading was a lost art, but I fear it may  be worse than I believed. Nobody reads anymore... if you dont like to read or dont have time- check out Librivox.org or Download the app- thousands of FREE, well read audiobooks- including Many E.R. Burroughs books like 'A Princess of Mars' and 'Tarzan of the Apes'... studies show listening to someone read has the same effects and benefits as doing the reading yourself- nothing to lose and every everything to gain.

text: Now that I've seen this trailer I find it puzzling that GHOSTBUSTERS is the movie people are whining "didn't need to be made." Ghostbusters looks like a fun shake-up of a concept worth revisiting, an idea whose potential has barely been explored on the big screen. But Tarzan? The concept is tired already, but this particular iteration looks so bland and uninteresting. Tarzan needs to be a grand adventure full of excitement and thrills, but this trailer paints the picture of a grey-tinted action piece that will only barely attempt to utilize its classic characters and themes.  But Ghostbusters stars a group of women, so naturally THAT is the one that gets a world of shit thrown at it. Oy.

I'm seeing a lot of CGI snobs which is just bullshit. I'd like to see any of you make anything better.   Fact is CGI is always gonna look fake, and do y'know why that is? BECAUSE IT'S EXACTLY THAT! I'm not negating the fact that it's not possible to make CGI animals look real, but we all bloody know it's fake and certain people are always gonna nitpick the shit outta that quality and scream "FAKE!" no matter what. They're assholes. Animation is a tricky thing and I think they did a great job when it was used.  This movie was nice to watch. It was atmospheric, it had subtle romance themes, it had it's funny moments that made me laugh out loud, plus the cast isn't bad to look at and they all have great chemistry with one another. text: Tips to improve the marketing for this film:  1. Show more of Jackson. He is the co-lead of the film, funny, a sharpshooter, etc. In fact, illustrate that the film is lighter and funnier than this trailer makes out. It's an adventure movie. His character also helps to ameliorate the intense "white savior" cliche of the Tarzan character throughout the film, but no one seeing this trailer would know that.  2. Explain the basic premise. There's nothing here about the Belgian kidnapping Jane to force Tarzan into a duel with Chief Labongo in order to get access to the diamonds, or about how Skarsgard and Jackson are fighting slavers throughout the film. You have to just kind of make up a premise in your head to explain what is happening on screen. Time is not a factor, because they have half this trailer dedicated to a scene that in the movie is over in a couple of minutes and is a flashback (Tarzan's origin). The movie does not dwell on his origin the way this trailer implies. We all know who Tarzan is and the movie understands that, but not the trailer. People may have been turned off by the idea of having to watch young Tarzan for 20 minutes before the movie gets going. That's not how the movie is structured at all, but the trailer makes it out to be that way.
